<section class="block-section do">
  <span class="section-tag">🛠️ Do</span>
  <h2>Today's work — choose one path</h2>
  <p class="sub">All four paths end with a named displacement risk in your plan and a concrete safeguard. The path is about how far you redesign to fix it.</p>
  <div class="choice-intro">
    <strong>Learning Intention:</strong> I can identify who my plan risks displacing and add a concrete equity safeguard to my recommendations.
  </div>
  <div class="choice-board">
    <div class="choice">
      <div class="choice-letter">A</div>
      <div class="choice-title">Name the risk, add a safeguard (default)</div>
      <div class="choice-detail">Find where your allocation displaces people or prices them out. Name it specifically (which residents, where, how). Then add one concrete safeguard to your recommendations: on-site rehousing, an affordability requirement, a protected settlement, phased change. A safeguard names what it does, not just that it cares.</div>
      <span class="udl-tag">Solo · Default</span>
    </div>
    <div class="choice">
      <div class="choice-letter">B</div>
      <div class="choice-title">Redesign to rehouse on-site (stretch)</div>
      <div class="choice-detail">Change your allocation so the people already there keep a place in the redesigned neighbourhood, and quantify what that protection costs elsewhere (fewer new units, less commercial frontage). Being able to say "I protected the settlement, and it cost me 2,000 of the new homes" is exactly the honest trade-off a planning audience trusts.</div>
      <span class="udl-tag">Solo · Stretch</span>
    </div>
    <div class="choice">
      <div class="choice-letter">C</div>
      <div class="choice-title">Equity & Resilience coached revision (choice)</div>
      <div class="choice-detail">Work the revision with the <a href="/ai-partners/equity-resilience-partner/">Equity &amp; Resilience Partner</a>. Let it press on who pays, then push back where it opposes all building. Land on a safeguard that protects people without freezing the plan. Document it.</div>
      <span class="udl-tag">Solo · Choice</span>
    </div>
    <div class="choice">
      <div class="choice-letter">D</div>
      <div class="choice-title">Peer-help — safeguard vs. slogan (practice)</div>
      <div class="choice-detail">If your safeguard sounds nice but does nothing, come to the peer-help table. A real safeguard changes the allocation or the recommendations in a way you can point to. Test yours against a partner's until both are concrete.</div>
      <span class="udl-tag">Pairs · Practice</span>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="block-section show">
  <span class="section-tag">📊 Show</span>
  <h2>What you're submitting today</h2>
  <p class="sub">A named displacement risk and a concrete safeguard. Specific beats well-meaning.</p>
  <div class="submission-callout">
    <div class="label">📥 Displacement risk + safeguard</div>
    <p>Two things: (1) a specific displacement or affordability risk in your plan (which residents, where, how it happens), and (2) one concrete safeguard you added to address it, named in a way a reader can check (what it does, who it protects, what it costs). "Be fair to residents" does not clear the bar; "rehouse the eri-side settlement in the new mid-rise on the same plots, funded through the corporation's housing budget" does.</p>
    <a href="#" class="rubric-link">Submit via Google Classroom →</a>
  </div>
  <p class="rubric-meta">
    <strong>Rubric link:</strong> facing displacement honestly is part of the Thinking and Transfer work on the <a href="/units/unit-6/assessment-sustainable-neighbourhood-plan/">Sustainable Neighbourhood Plan</a>: equity is one of the seven objectives, and a plan that hides its human cost is hiding a trade-off. See the <a href="/foundations/the-rubric/">rubric</a>.
  </p>
</section>

